				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\Delta A)$$\end{document} signal with respect to time delay showing the normalized pump-push-probe kinetics with a 1500 nm push-pulse and b 1630 nm push-pulse. Reproduced with permission from ref. 72, copyright (American Chemical Society, 2021).

The TRMC technique is commonly employed to examine the dynamics of photogenerated charge carriers in semiconductor materials characterized by low background conductivities. TRMC relies on the interaction between the mobile charge carriers and the electric field component of the microwaves, allowing for the determination of photoconductivity without the influence of interfacial effects between the perovskite film and the metallic electrodes. The schematic of TRMC measurement is shown in Fig. 11a. In a typical procedure, a laser pulse is used for the photoexcitation and generation of free carriers and/or excitons in the perovskite films. The mobile free carriers in the perovskite material interact with microwaves within a cavity, leading to the absorption of energy. This interaction causes a decrease in the microwave signal, allowing for the measurement of the photoconductance (△G\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
